<div id="review_828867495" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/828867495" />
    <a title="Jon Allen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3161147-jon-allen"><img alt="Jon Allen" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/828867495?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jon Allen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jon Allen" href="/user/show/3161147-jon-allen">Jon Allen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781299963184" href="/book/show/20535712-cracked">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3161147-jon-allen?shelf=psychology-sociology">psychology-sociology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3161147-jon-allen?shelf=science">science</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3161147-jon-allen?shelf=skepticism">skepticism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3161147-jon-allen?shelf=medicine">medicine</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer828867495" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13387243392706706350"><i>Cracked</i> covers very important issues psychiatry and defines the conflict that will shape the future of the field. The dispute between medical and critical psychiatric treatments is important to both practitioners and patients alike.<br/><br/>But while I agree with the author that these issues are important and need to be addressed, especially by the public at large, this book failed to enthrall me. Many of the interviews that the author recounts feel manipulative and staged. And some aspects of the discus</span>
  <span id="freeText13387243392706706350" style="display:none"><i>Cracked</i> covers very important issues psychiatry and defines the conflict that will shape the future of the field. The dispute between medical and critical psychiatric treatments is important to both practitioners and patients alike.<br /><br />But while I agree with the author that these issues are important and need to be addressed, especially by the public at large, this book failed to enthrall me. Many of the interviews that the author recounts feel manipulative and staged. And some aspects of the discussion feel brushed over or rushed pass. There are many good points raised in the book, but it was hard for me to separate them from the writing style.<br /><br />For something focused exclusively on reforming psychiatry, <i>Cracked</i> is a good choice. But for a more general look at the issues, I would recommend other works first.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13387243392706706350" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


