    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2801722221" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2801722221" />
    <a title="Bookz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/69809786-bookz"><img alt="Bookz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576455640p2/69809786.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2801722221?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bookz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bookz" href="/user/show/69809786-bookz">Bookz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/69809786-bookz?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/69809786-bookz?shelf=politics">politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2801722221" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17400304836269133218">This book isn&apos;t a critical analysis of psychiatry and the biological perspective of mental illness. It is more of a sensational attack on psychiatry - guilty of doing exactly what it criticizes psychiatry for - cherry picking. Davies picks whatever quotes from leading figures in psychiatry or whatever studies support his view that psychiatry is a hoax. Davies argues for example that antidepressants work no better than placebo and that there is no evidence for its biological basis, but within sec</span>
  <span id="freeText17400304836269133218" style="display:none">This book isn't a critical analysis of psychiatry and the biological perspective of mental illness. It is more of a sensational attack on psychiatry - guilty of doing exactly what it criticizes psychiatry for - cherry picking. Davies picks whatever quotes from leading figures in psychiatry or whatever studies support his view that psychiatry is a hoax. Davies argues for example that antidepressants work no better than placebo and that there is no evidence for its biological basis, but within seconds on the internet you can find much better evidence in favor of the biological perspective far superior than his "expert quotes". I'm a skeptic of the biological perspective and the toxic influence of the pharmaceutical industry, and I actually really enjoyed reading this book as I regrettably suppressed my doubts, but surely psychiatrists don't spend years in college studying complete lies. The book mentions how introduction to psychiatry textbooks highlight how limited our understanding is, then what are they even studying if not the biological evidence of mental illness? A major weakness to the book is its lack of a stronger argument in favor of medication which I feel surely exists. The book mentions occasionally, generally as quotes of psychiatrists which the writer is in agreement with, that medication has its use but among a very small proportion of the people who use the medication in reality. Yet, this is contrary to the apparent debunking of mental illness having any biological basis which can be treated with drugs. Davies didn't highlight how studying psychiatry requires a degree in medicine prior, therefore saying psychiatry needs to de-medicalize its understanding of suffering warrants not reform of the field but its complete collapse.<br /><br />I'm giving it 2 stars rather than 1 as I do agree with how distress shouldn't necessarily be medicalized, that we shouldn't export our model of understanding distress to other parts the world, that science and psychiatry desperately needs to detach from money-making institutions such as the pharmaceutical industry and that the DSM is rubbish... but the claims made on neurobiology and medication efficacy are completely one-sided, poorly researched and way too strong.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17400304836269133218" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

